  "summary": "A substantial modular social-justice Haggadah whose strongest passages connect familiar ritual actions to worker dignity, survivor leadership, shared responsibility, and the practical work of liberation. Its dated statistics, campaign references, graphic trafficking testimony, and many embedded contributors require selective use rather than wholesale insertion.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Rabbinic, activist, explanatory, and frequently testimonial, moving between traditional ritual interpretation and concrete human-rights organizing.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Beginner-friendly explanations of karpas, Maggid, Korekh, Tzafun, and Birkat Hamazon",
      "Social-justice and labor-rights thematic inserts grounded in a ritual action",
      "Prompts that center the leadership of people directly affected by injustice",
      "Longer adult or mixed-age Seders where a facilitator can hold difficult material"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The source assumes familiarity with advocacy organizations, labor policy, immigration law, and trafficking terminology.",
      "Several testimonies describe sexual exploitation, forced labor, racism, or deportation and need content notes and a genuine option to skip.",
      "Statistics and named campaigns date from the 2010s and must be labeled historically rather than presented as current facts.",
      "PDF headers, footnotes, image captions, and contributor transitions sometimes share a canonical segment with the reading itself."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "Use as a social-justice source, not as politically neutral ritual prose. Keep its commitments to dignity and worker-led change, identify dated U.S. policy material as historical, and exclude contemporary partisan claims from default generation. Biblical or liturgical references to Israel and Jerusalem are not modern nationalist claims, but no sequence here should introduce exclusive territorial language.",
    "creditContext": "Credit T'ruah and The Other Side of the River, The Other Side of the Sea on the final sources page. Preserve the printed contributor name for every selected passage and review embedded artwork, testimony, poems, songs, and quotations item by item as required by the source conditions."
  },
